The Friday Night Market in George Town is a fantastic experience full of life, colors, and delicious aromas! It perfectly captures the local Penang vibe -- friendly vendors, great street food, handmade crafts, and live music that creates a fun, festive atmosphere. The variety of snacks and local specialties is amazing, from satay to desserts and refreshing drinks. Prices are reasonable, and the crowd adds to the excitement rather than chaos. It's a great place to enjoy authentic Penang street culture, shop for souvenirs, and taste local favorites. review that it worth to visit and yes it is.
Lots of food stalls and there are kids wear, socks, sandals and mobile phone accessories along at pedestrian lot left and right side.
I try the egg waffle (6myr for 5pcs), fried stall (myr14.5 for around 6pcs radish cake, 6pcs dumpling, 2 otak-otak), steam dimsum (12myr for 10pcs), Yong tau fu in car (myr6 for 8pcs), pork satay for myr3.5/pcs.
Best one is steam dimsum, I quite confident saying it because even the seller eat the dimsum, I mean rarely to find someone who eat their own stuff but yet he is, either it is because he made it by himself or it is unpredictable delicious. Buy the one with plain colour more, because it taste more original.
2nd best is Yong tau fu, the chili and sauce is great.
Pork satay nice but have fishy taste (amis) there are 3 stall totally selling this pork satay the looks is same..
For fried stall quite interested in the beginning because the seller keep giving everyone 1pc free to try but when selling, they sell to me 3 kind of stuff and I must pay myr14.5 and eat till bored, so this fried stuff is nice if you eat it with more friends.
Egg waffle is nice too, but I think is just ordinary.
There is also socks stall that selling socks use bamboo so will not have bad odor after long usage, I don't buy it but the material is thick, maybe worth to try as other review saying Ling","reviewer_id":"115707001285123682601","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/115707001285123682601?hl=en-GB","rating":4,"review_text":"Heard that this night market only opens on a Friday by the locals, and I'm so glad we managed to visit this place while we are here!

It's a super long stretch (about 1km) of street vendors in tiny food trucks and tentage mainly selling traditional penang food and some street food typically found in Asian night markets.

On the opposite side sells slightly similar things, but mainly non-food items like clothes and phone equipment.

I would say this leans towards more of a local audience than tourists (compared to George Town), but variety is quite repetitive. For instance, there are 2 of the same brands selling sugar cane juice on the same stretch, and also Char Kueih Kak.

Prices wise, for each main, it is about 8RM onwards, but it's a pretty non-tourist place to get a quick fix of the local night market scene.

Though this place closes at 10pm, the stores start to pack up when they are done for the day around 9:15 pm onwards. still popular in many parts of the country. This flea market, known locally as Pasar Malam or Night Street Market, is a vibrant cultural experience that captures the essence of the local community.

The Macallum Night Market, located in Leboh Macallum, is quite exceptional. Here, you can find a mix of various makeshift stores selling all kinds of merchandise, from foodstuffs to entertainment. The street market is bustling with stalls from the local community selling different varieties of street food, whether traditional Malaysian hawker delights like char kway teow or nasi lemak, or modern fusion snacks. The affordability of prices and flavors makes it a foodie's paradise.

Each night market at a certain location can stretch to a mile long. Apart from food, you can buy other types of items be it clothes, accessories, and souvenirs, giving it a touch of uniqueness.

The market is well-organized, though it can get crowded during peak hours. Parking might be a problem since some of the parking lots have turned into store lots, so coming early makes a lot of sense to occupy those few available lots.

Trust me, if you want to experience some cheap thrills, this is the place for you.

If the review is of any help, please give me a LIKE for motivation. Open on select nights, this local night market offers a vibrant atmosphere with a wide range of street food options, from local favorites like char koay teow, apam balik, lok lok, and satay, to refreshing drinks and sweet treats.

Prices range from cheap to reasonable, making it perfect for budget-conscious foodies or tourists wanting to sample multiple dishes without breaking the bank.

It's also a great place to soak in the local culture, mingle with friendly vendors, and enjoy the bustling night scene. Whether you're a local or a visitor, this night market is a great one-stop spot to experience the flavors of Penang.

Tip: Go early to avoid the crowd and to get the freshest picks! [{"review_id":"ChZDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTUN3bGJMSk53EAE","review_link":"https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sChZDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTUN3bGJMSk53EAE!2m1!1s0x0:0x5ff87e27ddd7b3a5!3m1!1s2@1:CIHM0ogKEICAgMCwlbLJNw%7CCgwIuOjuvgYQgOiemQM%7C?hl=en-GB","name":"Jennifer","reviewer_id":"110520605084204408119","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/110520605084204408119?hl=en-GB","rating":5,"review_text":"Delicious and affordable local food at Farlim Night Market, which takes place every Wednesday! * Fried Carrot Cake (RM5)
* Muah Chee (RM4)
* Chicken Satay x2 (RM2)
* Sugarcane Juice (RM5)
* Pineapple Tart (RM1.20)
* Salted Fish Bun (RM4)
* Popcorn (RM6)
* Cold Beancurd (RM4.80)
* Grass Jelly (RM2.80)
* Fried Chicken Nugget (RM11)

I would highly recommend checking out the market if you are in Penang. The prices are very local as opposed to some touristy places. Chua","reviewer_id":"115818807181592198440","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/115818807181592198440?hl=en-GB","rating":4,"review_text":"Nice and simple night market with plenty of food choices & some goods to buy!
I think this night market is mostly for the locals as they featured food and daily necessities. Not really for tourists as they didn't have any souvenirs for purchase.
However, it was fun for us to see and try the food. Most of it was really yummy, but a lot of it was really unhealthy.
If you're a tourist and happen to be in Penang on a Wednesday, do try to make your way down and have some good local food! I at muah Chee, fried chicken drumstick, keropok lekor, dessert, durians, fried man tou, fried squid and had a super fresh freshly squeezed soursop juice. The juice was sour and yummy! Loved that.
If you're a local, for the sake of your health, pls don't come here more than once a month! Haha...
But it was good. [{"review_id":"Ci9DQUlRQUNvZENodHljRjlvT2poMlZuQlVSR3hhYm5RdFFVZDVVRGxPUlVSWVVtYxAB","review_link":"https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sCi9DQUlRQUNvZENodHljRjlvT2poMlZuQlVSR3hhYm5RdFFVZDVVRGxPUlVSWVVtYxAB!2m1!1s0x0:0x78fef512aaf0019f!3m1!1s2@1:CAIQACodChtycF9oOjh2VnBURGxabnQtQUd5UDlORURYUmc%7C0cXqtLBjlkD%7C?hl=en-GB","name":"Katrishaa Khylasanathan","reviewer_id":"107836078760682964151","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/107836078760682964151?hl=en-GB","rating":4,"review_text":"Had the curry mee at Air Itam Market Food Court and it really hit the spot!  The stall is run by an old aunty who cooks everything fresh upon order. I got the big bowl for RM7 came with plenty of sides like tofu puffs, cockles, and cuttlefish.

The broth was creamy, fragrant, and you can even request your spice level. It had that comforting, homemade taste , much better than the usual commercial-style versions. Portion was generous and definitely worth the price. I'll definitely return for this again , truly a hidden gem!
